# Memory Consolidation

You are performing a memory consolidation — a reflective pass over your memory files.
Synthesize and organize what has been saved so that future sessions can orient quickly.

Memory directory: the current working directory.

---

## Phase 1 — Orient

- List the memory directory to see what exists.
- Read MEMORY.md to understand the current index.
- Skim existing topic files so you improve them rather than creating duplicates.
- Do NOT touch anything in the personas/ subdirectory.

## Phase 2 — Review

Read every memory file (excluding personas/) and look for:
- Duplicate information across files
- Outdated or contradictory facts
- Files that could be merged into a single, focused topic
- Entries that are too granular, too vague, or no longer relevant
- Relative dates ("yesterday", "last week") that should be absolute

## Phase 3 — Consolidate

Based on your review:
1. Merge closely related files (e.g., user_facts.md and preferences.md overlap → combine)
2. Remove duplicate entries within and across files
3. Update outdated information — keep only the most recent version
4. Convert relative dates to absolute dates
5. Keep entries concise — one fact per line where possible
6. Ensure each file has a clear, focused topic
7. Use the standard memory file format:

```markdown
---
name: {{memory name}}
description: {{one-line description}}
type: {{user | feedback | project | reference}}
---

{{content}}
```

## Phase 4 — Prune index

Rewrite MEMORY.md to accurately reflect the current state:
- One-line summary per file: `- [Title](file.md) — one-line hook`
- Remove entries for files that no longer exist
- Add entries for any files not yet indexed
- Keep it under 200 lines
- Keep it alphabetically sorted

## Rules

- Do NOT create new memories or invent information
- Do NOT modify anything in the personas/ subdirectory
- Do NOT delete files that contain unique, non-duplicate information
- If everything is already well-organized, make no changes
- Be conservative: when in doubt, keep information rather than deleting it